00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:31.450
PROFESSOR: OK, so we're going
to talk about Six Sigma.

00:00:31.450 --> 00:00:33.490
Now, if you've seen,
the course is heavily

00:00:33.490 --> 00:00:37.690
weighted towards Lean with
a little bit of Six Sigma.

00:00:37.690 --> 00:00:41.770
And we think that's the
appropriate place to start.

00:00:41.770 --> 00:00:45.130
But we need to get you
started on Six Sigma.

00:00:45.130 --> 00:00:48.640
And so learning
objectives here are

00:00:48.640 --> 00:00:52.420
that Six Sigma is a valuable
approach for improving process

00:00:52.420 --> 00:00:53.730
quality.

00:00:53.730 --> 00:00:54.460
OK?

00:00:54.460 --> 00:00:57.067
And we'll try to explain a
little bit more about that.

00:00:57.067 --> 00:00:58.900
We're going to have you
be able to interpret

00:00:58.900 --> 00:01:01.850
a basic statistical
process control chart.

00:01:01.850 --> 00:01:05.170
That's what the active
learning experiment's about.

00:01:05.170 --> 00:01:07.510
We're going to talk about the
difference between process

00:01:07.510 --> 00:01:09.820
control limits and
specified control limits.

00:01:09.820 --> 00:01:12.670
And you'll be able to describe
what a capable process is.

00:01:12.670 --> 00:01:16.900
OK, so Six Sigma is a strategy
to improve process quality

00:01:16.900 --> 00:01:19.720
by identifying and
eliminating defects,

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:22.750
and defects in the broadest
possible sense, not just

00:01:22.750 --> 00:01:25.660
defects in the size of
a hole being drilled,

00:01:25.660 --> 00:01:30.630
but defect in something that you
want to deliver your customers,

00:01:30.630 --> 00:01:31.440
not what they want.

00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:32.170
That's a defect.

00:01:32.170 --> 00:01:33.480
OK?

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:35.860
It's a very
data-driven approach.

00:01:35.860 --> 00:01:37.240
So if you've seen
Lean-- in fact,

00:01:37.240 --> 00:01:39.448
one of the comments we got
back on the feedback sheet

00:01:39.448 --> 00:01:41.490
is it's kind of a lot
of touchy-feely stuff

00:01:41.490 --> 00:01:42.660
you're covering.

00:01:42.660 --> 00:01:45.600
And Lean is, in some ways,
a lot of touchy-feely stuff,

00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:47.700
because of the
importance of people.

00:01:47.700 --> 00:01:49.920
Six Sigma, if you
read the literature

00:01:49.920 --> 00:01:52.110
on Six Sigma, at least
the literature I've read,

00:01:52.110 --> 00:01:55.050
people are never mentioned.

00:01:55.050 --> 00:01:58.290
It's about a
problem-solving process.

00:01:58.290 --> 00:02:02.410
And that's important, but
it has its limitations.

00:02:02.410 --> 00:02:04.530
And the important thing
is to know when to use it

00:02:04.530 --> 00:02:08.440
and how it fits in with a
more holistic Lean approach.

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:10.930
And it's a very structured
implementation approach

00:02:10.930 --> 00:02:12.160
with certified experts.

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:14.452
You probably have heard of
black belts and green belts,

00:02:14.452 --> 00:02:15.580
and things like that, OK.

00:02:15.580 --> 00:02:18.490
So Six Sigma has this
hierarchy of experts.

00:02:18.490 --> 00:02:21.880
And that's really not
the mindset of Lean.

00:02:21.880 --> 00:02:25.840
The mindset of Lean is the
experts, the coach, not

00:02:25.840 --> 00:02:27.460
the person who knows the most.

00:02:27.460 --> 00:02:29.877
It's the person who gets the
most out of the people there.

00:02:29.877 --> 00:02:31.600
So there's some big
cultural differences

00:02:31.600 --> 00:02:33.477
between Six Sigma and Lean.

00:02:33.477 --> 00:02:35.560
But they've come together,
and the important thing

00:02:35.560 --> 00:02:38.950
is to try to understand that.

00:02:38.950 --> 00:02:40.883
Now, where does the
word sigma come from?

00:02:40.883 --> 00:02:42.550
Well, this is a pretty
analytical group,

00:02:42.550 --> 00:02:43.840
so you probably all know this.

00:02:43.840 --> 00:02:47.008
But a normal distribution,
something like what you just

00:02:47.008 --> 00:02:49.300
saw with the M&M's-- although
that wasn't quite normal,

00:02:49.300 --> 00:02:51.520
but it was somewhat
close to that--

00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:55.930
is defined by the standard
deviation, which is sigma.

00:02:55.930 --> 00:02:59.590
And in this chart-- so this
is one standard deviation

00:02:59.590 --> 00:03:02.410
from the mean, two standard
deviations, and three.

00:03:02.410 --> 00:03:05.395
And Six Sigma would be
six standard deviations.

00:03:05.395 --> 00:03:06.520
And just keep this in mind.

00:03:06.520 --> 00:03:08.500
We're going to deal with some
Three Sigma in a little bit,

00:03:08.500 --> 00:03:09.125
coming up here.

00:03:09.125 --> 00:03:12.620
Three Sigma is
99.73% of the area

00:03:12.620 --> 00:03:16.250
under a normal distribution,
would be within a Three Sigma

00:03:16.250 --> 00:03:16.750
band.

00:03:19.310 --> 00:03:19.810
OK.

00:03:19.810 --> 00:03:22.150
An important part of
Six Sigma is defects.

00:03:22.150 --> 00:03:26.500
Because the goal of Six Sigma is
to reduce the number of defects

00:03:26.500 --> 00:03:28.620
per million opportunities.

00:03:28.620 --> 00:03:31.980
And a defect is defined as any
process output that does not

00:03:31.980 --> 00:03:33.390
meet the customer
specifications,

00:03:33.390 --> 00:03:36.560
as I mentioned earlier,
in a very broad sense.

00:03:36.560 --> 00:03:37.343
OK?

00:03:37.343 --> 00:03:38.760
And so you've got
two things here.

00:03:38.760 --> 00:03:41.100
You've got opportunities
and defects.

00:03:41.100 --> 00:03:44.080
So you want to
reduce the defects,

00:03:44.080 --> 00:03:46.360
but you also, in
many ways, you want

00:03:46.360 --> 00:03:49.130
to reduce the number of
opportunities to have defects.

00:03:49.130 --> 00:03:51.940
OK, so reducing the
number of hand-offs--

00:03:51.940 --> 00:03:52.990
Sue mentioned the baton.

00:03:55.890 --> 00:03:59.910
Hand-offs between
people are always

00:03:59.910 --> 00:04:04.590
a potential source of mistakes
or errors or misunderstandings.

00:04:04.590 --> 00:04:07.020
Just think about how many
miscommunications have you

00:04:07.020 --> 00:04:09.660
had with your boyfriend
or girlfriend or parents

00:04:09.660 --> 00:04:11.400
or best friends.

00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:14.340
So hand-offs of any
kind are something

00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:17.718
that you want to minimize.

00:04:17.718 --> 00:04:19.260
I just read some
literature I'm going

00:04:19.260 --> 00:04:21.870
to share this with you, since
we're in the aviation field--

00:04:21.870 --> 00:04:24.270
I'm in the aviation field.

00:04:24.270 --> 00:04:28.370
The data from last year's
commercial air transport travel

00:04:28.370 --> 00:04:35.600
in the US was there was 0.02
fatalities for every million

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:40.010
boardings, 0.02.

00:04:40.010 --> 00:04:42.330
I think that's a nine sigma.

00:04:42.330 --> 00:04:44.060
Yeah, OK.

00:04:44.060 --> 00:04:46.220
So that gives you kind of
a benchmark of something

00:04:46.220 --> 00:04:46.970
being really good.

00:04:46.970 --> 00:04:49.800
But how good is good?

00:04:49.800 --> 00:04:52.095
Some people say, you
know, 99% is good.

00:04:52.095 --> 00:04:54.785
I mean, If my car
starts 99% of the time,

00:04:54.785 --> 00:04:56.160
and it's an old
car, that's good.

00:04:56.160 --> 00:04:57.930
But that's three
days out of the year,

00:04:57.930 --> 00:04:59.190
I'm not going to get
out of my garage,

00:04:59.190 --> 00:05:01.190
and I'm going to miss
getting to my appointment.

00:05:01.190 --> 00:05:03.000
OK, that's not so good.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.130
So 99% you might think is good.

00:05:05.130 --> 00:05:09.090
But that's 20,000 lost
article of mail per hour;

00:05:09.090 --> 00:05:11.160
unsafe drinking water
for 15 minutes a day;

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:13.980
in this audience, 5,000
incorrect surgical operations

00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:17.820
per week; two short
or long landings

00:05:17.820 --> 00:05:21.690
at a major airport each
day; 200,000 wrong drug

00:05:21.690 --> 00:05:23.160
prescriptions a year.

00:05:23.160 --> 00:05:26.640
That's not really
very good, 99%.

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:28.200
This is much better, Six Sigma.

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:30.180
This is what you're looking for.

00:05:30.180 --> 00:05:31.710
OK?

00:05:31.710 --> 00:05:35.010
1.7 incorrect operations per
week-- even that's too much.

00:05:35.010 --> 00:05:38.830
But boy, that's a lot
better than 5,000.

00:05:38.830 --> 00:05:41.860
If you're one of
those 1.7 people,

00:05:41.860 --> 00:05:43.540
you don't care what sigma it is.

00:05:43.540 --> 00:05:44.380
You just got--

00:05:44.380 --> 00:05:46.930
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:46.930 --> 00:05:47.793
Same here.

00:05:47.793 --> 00:05:49.210
And as I mentioned,
airline travel

00:05:49.210 --> 00:05:52.720
is nine sigma for safety.

00:05:52.720 --> 00:05:56.560
OK, so a basic tool
in Six Sigma is

00:05:56.560 --> 00:05:58.940
called the statistical
process control chart.

00:05:58.940 --> 00:06:00.580
So a chart shows--
so it's a sequence.

00:06:00.580 --> 00:06:02.190
This is a time chart.

00:06:02.190 --> 00:06:03.940
And we're going to
build one just shortly.

00:06:03.940 --> 00:06:05.607
It's time, and this
is some measurement.

00:06:05.607 --> 00:06:08.800
And this shows how stable
it is, how much it's

00:06:08.800 --> 00:06:10.780
tending to be around
the center of the chart.

00:06:10.780 --> 00:06:13.260
It's a very common chart.

00:06:13.260 --> 00:06:16.360
And in both fields, if you go
into a production facility,

00:06:16.360 --> 00:06:20.170
an engineering, production
facility, now the operator

00:06:20.170 --> 00:06:23.830
will be showing you
their control chart.

00:06:23.830 --> 00:06:27.190
I couldn't believe, when I first
went in and saw the machinist

00:06:27.190 --> 00:06:32.270
proudly or the machine operators
showing me their control chart.

00:06:32.270 --> 00:06:35.150
I see control charts
all through health care.

00:06:35.150 --> 00:06:37.885
So let's make a control chart.

00:06:37.885 --> 00:06:39.760
OK, so we're going to
do a little experiment,

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:42.412
a little thing here.

00:06:42.412 --> 00:06:44.620
We're going to put it in
the framework of a pharmacy.

00:06:44.620 --> 00:06:47.177
For those of you who are not in
the framework of health care,

00:06:47.177 --> 00:06:48.760
you could think of
another application

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:50.230
where you're getting something.

00:06:50.230 --> 00:06:54.190
But our pharmacy here dispenses
a medicine called a White Bean

00:06:54.190 --> 00:06:56.380
Medicine.

00:06:56.380 --> 00:07:00.350
And we get it in bulk from
two different suppliers.

00:07:00.350 --> 00:07:04.900
This is our brand
name supplier, Goya.

00:07:04.900 --> 00:07:06.690
And it appears to
come from Spain.

00:07:06.690 --> 00:07:09.190
It's a little hard to tell what
the original source is here.

00:07:09.190 --> 00:07:11.245
But at the end of it,
there's some Spanish,

00:07:11.245 --> 00:07:13.450
and so I presume it
comes from Spain.

00:07:13.450 --> 00:07:15.460
And this is our
generic supplier,

00:07:15.460 --> 00:07:19.893
[? Shaw's. ?] So we get
these two suppliers.

00:07:19.893 --> 00:07:22.060
And if you read the back
of the [? Shaw's-- ?] well,

00:07:22.060 --> 00:07:24.477
you can read the back of the
label, if you need to, later.

00:07:24.477 --> 00:07:27.520
So our pharmacy gets it
and puts it in these bins.

00:07:27.520 --> 00:07:31.760
And then they've decided to
measure dosages by volume.

00:07:31.760 --> 00:07:34.050
Now, usually a
dosage is by weight.

00:07:34.050 --> 00:07:35.200
OK?

00:07:35.200 --> 00:07:39.437
But it's much easier just
to scoop this up and fill it

00:07:39.437 --> 00:07:41.770
than to scoop it up and fill
it and weigh it, and so on.

00:07:41.770 --> 00:07:43.600
So we're doing it by volume.

00:07:43.600 --> 00:07:47.830
And what we want to do is to
track our pharmacy dispensary,

00:07:47.830 --> 00:07:53.270
to be sure that we're
getting consistent weight.

00:07:53.270 --> 00:07:55.490
And so our pharmacy--

00:07:55.490 --> 00:07:59.720
this is not a critical
medicine, but it's widely

00:07:59.720 --> 00:08:00.970
used in our facility.

00:08:00.970 --> 00:08:03.360
So we dispense a
lot of it each day.

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:04.970
And so what we've
done in our pharmacy

00:08:04.970 --> 00:08:08.990
is our pharmacy is going to take
three samples of this medicine

00:08:08.990 --> 00:08:11.238
each day and weigh it.

00:08:11.238 --> 00:08:13.280
And the next day, it will
take three more samples

00:08:13.280 --> 00:08:13.820
and weigh it.

00:08:13.820 --> 00:08:16.190
And we're going to build this
chart to see what it's like.

00:08:16.190 --> 00:08:17.990
And the pharmacy has
been very cooperative.

00:08:17.990 --> 00:08:20.970
They've given us 20 samples,
that are already on your table.

00:08:20.970 --> 00:08:23.000
OK?

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:24.750
And then I'm going to
tell you what to do.

00:08:24.750 --> 00:08:26.107
We're going to enter this data.

00:08:26.107 --> 00:08:27.440
So we've got a three-cup sample.

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:30.380
We're going to enter data
into control charts-- one

00:08:30.380 --> 00:08:33.350
for the average weight and one
for the range of the weight

00:08:33.350 --> 00:08:35.270
of the three cups.

00:08:35.270 --> 00:08:36.860
And we're going to
use it for 20 days

00:08:36.860 --> 00:08:39.326
to establish our
process capability.

00:08:39.326 --> 00:08:40.909
So we're going to
measure for 20 days,

00:08:40.909 --> 00:08:42.284
and then that's
going to tell us,

00:08:42.284 --> 00:08:43.490
do we have a stable process?

00:08:43.490 --> 00:08:46.078
And we can monitor after that.

00:08:46.078 --> 00:08:47.620
And so that's what
we're going to do.

00:08:47.620 --> 00:08:52.130
So our first phase is now each
of you are going to weigh this.

00:08:52.130 --> 00:08:54.080
You each have four days.

00:08:54.080 --> 00:08:57.560
In the center of your
table, you have 12 cups.

00:08:57.560 --> 00:09:00.950
And the cups, there are
three cups for each day.

00:09:00.950 --> 00:09:03.230
It says right on
there, this is day 16.

00:09:03.230 --> 00:09:05.120
There are three day 16 cups.

00:09:05.120 --> 00:09:06.870
And you have a sheet.

00:09:06.870 --> 00:09:09.810
And your sheet
says, here's day 16.

00:09:09.810 --> 00:09:13.320
So you measure cup A, B, C.
You compute the average--

00:09:13.320 --> 00:09:15.600
we can get some calculators,
if you need it--

00:09:15.600 --> 00:09:17.860
the max and the min
and then the range,

00:09:17.860 --> 00:09:19.320
which is the max minus the min.

00:09:19.320 --> 00:09:22.290
And then you bring that
up here to data central.

00:09:22.290 --> 00:09:24.720
And we'll record it.

00:09:24.720 --> 00:09:26.550
And you have a scale.

00:09:26.550 --> 00:09:27.900
And you want to use grams.

00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:31.780
This is in pounds and kilograms.

00:09:31.780 --> 00:09:34.840
You want to use the kilograms
scale to get it in grams.

00:09:34.840 --> 00:09:36.280
And don't use this now.

00:09:36.280 --> 00:09:38.738
But when we're all finished,
we'll dump the beans in there.

00:09:38.738 --> 00:09:40.720
But don't do it
now, because we may

00:09:40.720 --> 00:09:43.160
need to go back and do
some second measurements.

00:09:43.160 --> 00:09:47.380
OK, so please now start at your
tables measuring these samples,

00:09:47.380 --> 00:09:50.480
filling out the chart,
and bringing it up here.

00:09:50.480 --> 00:09:52.956
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:10:06.550 --> 00:10:07.420
STUDENT: 98.

00:10:07.420 --> 00:10:08.462
STUDENT: Oh, my goodness.

00:10:12.088 --> 00:10:12.880
STUDENT: Excellent.

00:10:12.880 --> 00:10:15.087
Very [? well done. ?]

00:10:15.087 --> 00:10:15.670
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:10:15.670 --> 00:10:18.400
So we have all the data.

00:10:18.400 --> 00:10:24.660
And my helper over here
is going to enter it day

00:10:24.660 --> 00:10:27.690
by day, so it unfolds like
you would see a normal control

00:10:27.690 --> 00:10:29.940
chart, if you're
watching it day by day.

00:10:29.940 --> 00:10:32.400
So he's now on day five.

00:10:32.400 --> 00:10:37.080
Now, what we have-- this
is the mean average.

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:39.330
This is the average,
and this is the range.

00:10:39.330 --> 00:10:40.890
And this is the
mean of the average,

00:10:40.890 --> 00:10:42.640
and this is the
mean of the range.

00:10:42.640 --> 00:10:43.530
OK?

00:10:43.530 --> 00:10:46.590
And then what we have
here are these red lines

00:10:46.590 --> 00:10:49.060
are the Three Sigma lines.

00:10:49.060 --> 00:10:51.240
Remember, on a
normal distribution,

00:10:51.240 --> 00:10:52.860
I said Three Sigma.

00:10:52.860 --> 00:10:57.600
So the way these control charts
work is you get this data.

00:10:57.600 --> 00:11:01.080
And it's been established
that the processes--

00:11:01.080 --> 00:11:03.630
you look at a three
sigma deviation.

00:11:03.630 --> 00:11:07.390
And as long as you're within
that three sigma deviation,

00:11:07.390 --> 00:11:09.510
your process is under control.

00:11:09.510 --> 00:11:13.840
OK, that's just sort
of what's evolved.

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:16.390
And of course,
these red lines will

00:11:16.390 --> 00:11:18.940
change as he enters
the data, because he's

00:11:18.940 --> 00:11:21.210
getting more and more samples.

00:11:21.210 --> 00:11:23.840
So this is like watching
the election returns

00:11:23.840 --> 00:11:24.680
on election eve.

00:11:24.680 --> 00:11:25.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:25.610 --> 00:11:27.470
STUDENT: We're all
[? down here. ?]

00:11:27.470 --> 00:11:29.446
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:11:29.446 --> 00:11:32.750
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:32.750 --> 00:11:34.372
PROFESSOR: So
we're up to day 10.

00:11:34.372 --> 00:11:37.180
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:37.180 --> 00:11:39.430
PROFESSOR: OK, and what's
going on in the background--

00:11:39.430 --> 00:11:40.960
one of our colleagues
at Cal Poly

00:11:40.960 --> 00:11:42.260
put this spreadsheet together.

00:11:42.260 --> 00:11:46.660
So this shows the [? app, ?]
the mean, what's called x bar.

00:11:46.660 --> 00:11:49.030
This is x bar,
and this is r bar.

00:11:49.030 --> 00:11:54.130
X is the average,
and r is the range.

00:11:54.130 --> 00:11:56.650
And then we've got the upper
and lower control limits.

00:11:56.650 --> 00:11:59.050
These are called upper control
limits and lower control

00:11:59.050 --> 00:11:59.695
limits.

00:11:59.695 --> 00:12:02.260
We've got the upper and lower
control limits for the average

00:12:02.260 --> 00:12:03.040
