00:27:54.900 --> 00:27:57.640
OK, so now our last topic--

00:27:57.640 --> 00:27:59.790
this is Process Capability.

00:27:59.790 --> 00:28:02.220
Process Capability is defined
as the ability of a process

00:28:02.220 --> 00:28:04.720
to meet the customer
expectations.

00:28:04.720 --> 00:28:07.402
And what we have here is we
know what the capability is,

00:28:07.402 --> 00:28:09.360
but we don't know whether
it meets the customer

00:28:09.360 --> 00:28:10.170
expectations.

00:28:10.170 --> 00:28:13.060
And to get the customer
expectations on there,

00:28:13.060 --> 00:28:14.850
we have to find
out what they want.

00:28:14.850 --> 00:28:16.200
HUGH MCMANUS: The
customer-determined limit,

00:28:16.200 --> 00:28:18.575
the spec limits, are essentially
what the customer wants.

00:28:18.575 --> 00:28:20.310
The upper and lower
values between which

00:28:20.310 --> 00:28:23.790
a process must be controlled--
that's what the customer wants.

00:28:23.790 --> 00:28:27.390
The bounds in which we choose
to control the process,

00:28:27.390 --> 00:28:29.340
or which we try to
control the process,

00:28:29.340 --> 00:28:33.430
are the upper and lower
control limits of the process.

00:28:33.430 --> 00:28:36.720
So how do we measure, given
those two definitions,

00:28:36.720 --> 00:28:39.010
the process capability?

00:28:39.010 --> 00:28:41.160
One way to do it is to
think about the process.

00:28:41.160 --> 00:28:42.700
And again, this is
an approximation.

00:28:42.700 --> 00:28:46.110
But it's a pretty good one,
under a lot of circumstances.

00:28:46.110 --> 00:28:48.910
The process is having a
normally distributed behavior.

00:28:48.910 --> 00:28:51.090
So if we collect
some data, we can

00:28:51.090 --> 00:28:55.950
assume a normal distribution,
do some statistics using

00:28:55.950 --> 00:28:58.740
our statistical
tools, and decide

00:28:58.740 --> 00:29:01.650
how good or bad the process is.

00:29:01.650 --> 00:29:05.130
And if we have a normally
distributed process,

00:29:05.130 --> 00:29:07.560
its behavior is going
to be characterized

00:29:07.560 --> 00:29:10.120
by its standard
deviation, sigma.

00:29:10.120 --> 00:29:12.792
And if we draw our spec
limits around that normal

00:29:12.792 --> 00:29:14.625
distribution-- here is
our lower spec limit,

00:29:14.625 --> 00:29:16.950
and here's our
upper spec limit--

00:29:16.950 --> 00:29:25.170
we can define a quantity
CP, the process capability,

00:29:25.170 --> 00:29:29.250
which is essentially this
distance here, the upper limit

00:29:29.250 --> 00:29:31.090
less this lower spec limit--

00:29:31.090 --> 00:29:33.450
so that the range
which is acceptable

00:29:33.450 --> 00:29:37.000
divided by the Six
Sigma of the process.

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:43.470
And if we have, say, a CP
of 2, that's a very tight.

00:29:43.470 --> 00:29:48.630
Basically, the spec limits are
twice Six Sigma of the process.

00:29:48.630 --> 00:29:51.060
Then it's a very
tight distribution

00:29:51.060 --> 00:29:52.770
inside the spec limits.

00:29:52.770 --> 00:29:55.860
And the chance of something bad
happening are very, very small,

00:29:55.860 --> 00:29:57.170
the chance of going out.

00:29:57.170 --> 00:30:00.395
So a CP of 2 is a
very good process.

00:30:00.395 --> 00:30:01.020
That, in fact--

00:30:01.020 --> 00:30:03.398
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE] Six
Sigma is [INAUDIBLE]----

00:30:03.398 --> 00:30:04.440
HUGH MCMANUS: Six Sigma--

00:30:04.440 --> 00:30:05.580
STUDENT: --standard
deviations [INAUDIBLE]..

00:30:05.580 --> 00:30:07.747
HUGH MCMANUS: That's right--
six standard deviations

00:30:07.747 --> 00:30:09.990
on either side of
the mean, right.

00:30:09.990 --> 00:30:13.260
So a CP of 2 would be
a Six Sigma process.

00:30:13.260 --> 00:30:15.563
In that sense, it would
be a very good one.

00:30:15.563 --> 00:30:16.980
And just graphically,
you can just

00:30:16.980 --> 00:30:19.740
see there's basically no tail
sticking out of the bad zone.

00:30:19.740 --> 00:30:22.560
CP of 1 means you've got
three sigma on each side.

00:30:22.560 --> 00:30:28.050
Three sigma, you've got 97 point
whatever percent of the process

00:30:28.050 --> 00:30:29.500
falling in that range.

00:30:29.500 --> 00:30:31.770
So the chance of something
falling outside the range

00:30:31.770 --> 00:30:33.090
is quite small.

00:30:33.090 --> 00:30:34.020
But it's not 0.

00:30:34.020 --> 00:30:35.670
We can see a little
bit of ink here

00:30:35.670 --> 00:30:38.500
outside of the acceptable range.

00:30:38.500 --> 00:30:40.860
And once we get below 1,
it starts getting ugly.

00:30:40.860 --> 00:30:43.920
We really don't want to
even talk about that--

00:30:43.920 --> 00:30:48.280
so from a statistical process
control point of view.

00:30:48.280 --> 00:30:51.420
Another issue which
one can ignore

00:30:51.420 --> 00:30:54.690
is the fact that we
may not be centered.

00:30:54.690 --> 00:30:59.760
And we can actually redefine
our process capability

00:30:59.760 --> 00:31:03.600
using a metric called CPK,
which takes into a fact

00:31:03.600 --> 00:31:06.270
that we may drift off mean.

00:31:06.270 --> 00:31:07.440
And it's defined this way.

00:31:07.440 --> 00:31:13.380
It's basically the distance to
the closer boundary from where

00:31:13.380 --> 00:31:15.540
we are divided by three sigma.

00:31:15.540 --> 00:31:18.190
And it's whichever
one of those is worse.

00:31:18.190 --> 00:31:22.980
And those same curves
shifted over 1 and 1/2 sigma

00:31:22.980 --> 00:31:25.080
look a lot less pretty.

00:31:25.080 --> 00:31:30.120
Our former Six Sigma process
now has a CPK at 1.5.

00:31:30.120 --> 00:31:31.873
But it's still OK.

00:31:31.873 --> 00:31:33.540
There's a tiny, tiny--
there's a couple,

00:31:33.540 --> 00:31:36.150
like two pixels worth of
ink sticking out there.

00:31:36.150 --> 00:31:40.620
The chance of a defect is
still very, very small.

00:31:40.620 --> 00:31:46.110
But our formally
OK-looking CP of 1 process

00:31:46.110 --> 00:31:49.290
now has quite a
bad-looking tail.

00:31:49.290 --> 00:31:53.090
And our process that
was bad is now horrible,

00:31:53.090 --> 00:31:55.113
our relatively
uncontrolled process.

00:31:55.113 --> 00:31:57.530
So that's a different way of
measuring process capability,

00:31:57.530 --> 00:32:00.740
which takes into account the
fact that the mean may not

00:32:00.740 --> 00:32:02.390
be on the center.

00:32:02.390 --> 00:32:08.450
What we do with these two
measures is different.

00:32:08.450 --> 00:32:10.730
Here we have a archery example.

00:32:10.730 --> 00:32:17.090
This is a classic statistically
characterize-able process.

00:32:17.090 --> 00:32:19.220
We have shots that
are both widely

00:32:19.220 --> 00:32:21.650
dispersed and off-center.

00:32:21.650 --> 00:32:24.630
So how would we
characterize that?

00:32:24.630 --> 00:32:26.640
It's basically low on
both metrics, right?

00:32:26.640 --> 00:32:31.490
It's widely dispersed,
and it's off-center.

00:32:31.490 --> 00:32:35.340
Here's another archer.

00:32:35.340 --> 00:32:39.407
It has a tight distribution,
but it's way off-center.

00:32:39.407 --> 00:32:40.900
STUDENT: So CP is high.

00:32:40.900 --> 00:32:43.610
HUGH MCMANUS: So CP is
high, and CPK is low.

00:32:43.610 --> 00:32:44.170
That's right.

00:32:44.170 --> 00:32:46.868
So that's the difference
between those metrics.

00:32:46.868 --> 00:32:48.160
On this metric, it looks great.

00:32:48.160 --> 00:32:50.140
On that metric, it does not.

00:32:50.140 --> 00:32:53.300
And this, of course,
is what we want.

00:32:53.300 --> 00:32:56.680
If you're an archer or
any other person who

00:32:56.680 --> 00:33:01.790
needs to control their
process, what do you do first?

00:33:01.790 --> 00:33:03.770
Yeah, I'm cheating a
little bit on this one.

00:33:03.770 --> 00:33:06.440
I do archery sometimes,
not very much.

00:33:06.440 --> 00:33:08.630
But you have to do
this first, actually.

00:33:08.630 --> 00:33:10.820
You have to get your
process repeatable,

00:33:10.820 --> 00:33:12.920
even if the meat is way off.

00:33:12.920 --> 00:33:15.290
Because if you're
correcting every time,

00:33:15.290 --> 00:33:18.150
then it just goes
all over the place.

00:33:18.150 --> 00:33:23.200
But if you just go, OK,
same thing every time, OK.

00:33:23.200 --> 00:33:25.630
Five times in a row, I've
hit up and to the right.

00:33:25.630 --> 00:33:26.740
Now I'm going to adjust.

00:33:29.290 --> 00:33:34.060
So often, you concentrate on
knocking your CP down first,

00:33:34.060 --> 00:33:36.580
to understand your process,
to see where the mean is.

00:33:36.580 --> 00:33:38.350
Because you can't
really measure the mean

00:33:38.350 --> 00:33:41.200
in a situation like-- you can
statistically, but it's hard.

00:33:41.200 --> 00:33:43.480
OK, enough of that.

00:33:46.890 --> 00:33:49.860
This actually-- remember
we said we would--

00:33:49.860 --> 00:33:52.530
I'd tell you where the
definition of Six Sigma

00:33:52.530 --> 00:33:53.190
comes from.

00:33:53.190 --> 00:33:57.810
Interestingly, it
comes from a process

00:33:57.810 --> 00:34:00.270
with a mean shift
of 1 and 1/2, which

00:34:00.270 --> 00:34:04.660
would give you three defects
per million opportunities.

00:34:04.660 --> 00:34:06.630
So if you have a
very good process,

00:34:06.630 --> 00:34:11.790
but you still don't control
your mean to more than 1

00:34:11.790 --> 00:34:17.880
and 1/2 sigma, you still have
a very low defects per million.

00:34:17.880 --> 00:34:19.949
That's where that
idea comes from.

00:34:19.949 --> 00:34:21.540
Those are some of
the concepts that we

00:34:21.540 --> 00:34:25.260
use to get processes under
control and keep them there.

00:34:25.260 --> 00:34:31.560
And Six Sigma, as
an overall method,

00:34:31.560 --> 00:34:36.030
is very useful for taking
variation down, especially

00:34:36.030 --> 00:34:40.800
in critical applications like
large-scale manufacturing

00:34:40.800 --> 00:34:44.190
or health care, where you want
your defects to be very low,

00:34:44.190 --> 00:34:45.832
your variation to be very low.

00:34:45.832 --> 00:34:47.790
We've talked to you about
control charts, which

00:34:47.790 --> 00:34:49.610
is a great place to start.

00:34:49.610 --> 00:34:50.469
It's not the end.

00:34:50.469 --> 00:34:53.730
And we've glossed over
all the statistical tools

00:34:53.730 --> 00:34:55.739
you need to really
understand the numbers.

00:34:55.739 --> 00:34:59.550
But the visual is very
powerful in and of itself.

00:34:59.550 --> 00:35:01.140
Even if you don't
do the statistics,

00:35:01.140 --> 00:35:04.590
having the visual evidence
of what your process can do

00:35:04.590 --> 00:35:06.435
and whether it's deviating
is very powerful.

